# Summary
A security bug was introduced by adding the `Prepare version` step with direct unsanitized `${{ github.ref_name }}` interpolation into PowerShell. This creates a new command-injection sink and feeds attacker-controlled output into the later build command.
The release job runs on tag pushes matching `v*` and grants `contents: write`. This commit adds a `Prepare version` PowerShell step that embeds `${{ github.ref_name }}` directly into a double-quoted PowerShell string, then uses the resulting output in another PowerShell command. Git tag names can contain characters such as double quotes, semicolons, `#`, and redirection characters, so a tag such as `v";whoami;#` can break out of the string and execute arbitrary PowerShell on the release runner. Because this job builds and publishes release artifacts with a write-scoped GitHub token, command execution here can tamper with official release assets. The workflow also still contains older direct `${{ github.ref_name }}` interpolations in packaging paths, so the tag name should be validated or passed through environment variables and treated strictly as data.

# Validation
## Rubric
- [x] Confirm the release workflow is security-sensitive: tag-triggered on `v*` and has `contents: write` permissions.
- [x] Confirm the commit added a new `Prepare version` PowerShell step that directly interpolates `${{ github.ref_name }}` into executable script text.
- [x] Confirm an attacker-controlled tag containing PowerShell metacharacters is a valid git tag and matches the `v*` trigger.
- [x] Render the vulnerable workflow command with the malicious tag and show it produces a separate injected PowerShell statement.
- [ ] Dynamically execute the rendered script under PowerShell; skipped because `pwsh`/`powershell` is not installed in the container.
## Report
Validated the suspected GitHub Actions PowerShell command injection. The workflow at `.github/workflows/release.yml:3-10` runs on tag pushes matching `v*` and grants `contents: write`. The newly added step at `.github/workflows/release.yml:57-63` uses `shell: pwsh` and directly interpolates `${{ github.ref_name }}` into a double-quoted PowerShell string: `"app_version=${{ github.ref_name }}.$shortSha" >> $env:GITHUB_OUTPUT`. I verified that a malicious tag name is accepted by git: `git check-ref-format 'refs/tags/v";whoami>pwned.txt;#'` returned 0, and creating/listing the local tag produced `v";whoami>pwned.txt;#`. GitHub Actions expression interpolation happens before PowerShell execution, so this tag renders the Prepare version script as: `$shortSha = "2a3fa25208bf983fe95ee6782866790fa0af64eb".Substring(0, 7)` followed by `"app_version=v";whoami>pwned.txt;#.$shortSha" >> $env:GITHUB_OUTPUT`. In PowerShell, the injected double quote closes the string, `;` starts a new statement, `whoami>pwned.txt` executes, and `#` comments out the remaining suffix/redirection. This confirms arbitrary command execution in the release runner context. I also confirmed the commit introduced this new `Prepare version` sink via `git show`, although the parent workflow already had older unsanitized `github.ref_name` interpolations in build/package commands. Dynamic execution with PowerShell was not possible in this Linux container because `pwsh`/`powershell` is not installed; `gdb` and `valgrind` are also unavailable and not applicable to this CI YAML command-injection issue.

